INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e736c1cb-6752-4066-973b-ad24bcff635b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Pandas .plot() — Unlock Matplotlib's Figure/Axes API for Publication-Quality Charts$escape$,
  $escape$Every pandas DataFrame has a .plot() method that returns a Matplotlib Axes object. Most developers stop at df.plot() and miss the full power underneath. The key: pass an explicit Axes via the ax= parameter to control layout, styling, and multi-panel figures.

Create a Figure and Axes grid with plt.subplots(), then route each pandas plot call to a specific panel. This gives you full control over titles, axis labels, tick formatting, and shared scales — things that matter when your chart leaves a notebook and enters a report or paper.

For publication quality, call fig.set_dpi(300), use ax.set_xlabel() with fontsize, and apply ax.spines removal for cleaner aesthetics. The pandas plotting backend respects all standard Matplotlib rcParams, so you can set a global style with plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid') before any .plot() call.

Critical detail: .plot() returns the Axes, so you can chain further Matplotlib customization directly on the return value without ever importing axes manually.$escape$,
  $escape$import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(30, 3), columns=['A', 'B', 'C']).cumsum()

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 4), dpi=150)

df.plot(ax=axes[0], title='Cumulative Trends')
axes[0].set_ylabel('Value')

df.corrwith(df['A']).drop('A').plot.bar(ax=axes[1], title='Correlation with A')
axes[1].axhline(0, color='gray', linewidth=0.8)

for ax in axes:
    ax.spines[['top', 'right']].set_visible(False)

fig.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('pandas_pub_chart.png', bbox_inches='tight')$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
