INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd20c40b4-a94a-4d15-8502-7bfe327de8a3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Pandas + Seaborn — Plot DataFrames Without Reshaping$escape$,
  $escape$Seaborn reads pandas DataFrames natively, so you can skip the NumPy detour and pass column names as strings directly to plot parameters. The real power is in long-form (tidy) data — use df.melt() to pivot wide DataFrames into Seaborn-friendly shape, then map columns to x, y, and hue without manual indexing.

Seaborn's statistical estimators (mean, confidence intervals) operate on grouped DataFrame rows automatically. Pair sns.catplot() with a GroupBy-aggregated frame for multi-panel categorical breakdowns. For time series, pass a DatetimeIndex column to x and Seaborn handles tick formatting.

Themes apply globally via sns.set_theme(), but per-plot styling works best through matplotlib axes returned by every Seaborn function — chain .set_title() or .set_xlim() directly. Use sns.FacetGrid with a pandas column for small multiples without manual subplot loops.

Key pattern: keep your DataFrame tidy (one observation per row), and Seaborn does the grouping, aggregation, and layout. If you're calling .values or .to_numpy() before plotting, you're likely overcomplicating it.$escape$,
  $escape$import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

df = pd.DataFrame({
    "day": ["Mon","Tue","Wed"] * 3,
    "metric": ["latency","latency","latency","throughput","throughput","throughput","errors","errors","errors"],
    "value": [120, 95, 110, 500, 530, 510, 3, 1, 4]
})

# No reshaping needed — pass column names directly
g = sns.catplot(data=df, x="day", y="value", col="metric",
               kind="bar", sharey=False, height=3)
g.set_titles("{col_name}")
g.set_axis_labels("Day", "")$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
