INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '031951e5-f0fd-4774-b81f-2af5ac47336f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Pandas plot() — Choosing Charts, Fixing Colors, and Killing Chartjunk$escape$,
  $escape$DataFrame.plot() defaults to line charts for everything, which is wrong half the time. Match chart type to data shape: use `.plot.bar()` for categorical comparisons, `.plot.scatter()` for two continuous variables, `.plot.hist()` for distributions, and `.plot.area()` for cumulative trends. Never use `.plot.pie()` — it's perceptually broken for comparing slices.

For color accessibility, ditch the default matplotlib palette. Pass `colormap='viridis'` or `colormap='cividis'` to any `.plot()` call — both are colorblind-safe and perceptually uniform. For categorical data, use `color=['#0072B2','#E69F00','#009E73']` (Okabe-Ito palette).

Kill chartjunk by chaining matplotlib calls on the returned Axes object: remove gridlines with `ax.grid(False)`, strip the top/right spines with `ax.spines[['top','right']].set_visible(False)`, and set `legend=False` when there's only one series. Use `rot=0` to keep x-labels horizontal. Every decoration should earn its pixels.$escape$,
  $escape$import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df = pd.DataFrame({"lang": ["Python","Rust","Go","TS"], "stars": [95,78,62,88]})

ax = df.plot.bar(
    x="lang", y="stars",
    colormap="cividis", legend=False, rot=0,
    title="GitHub Stars by Language"
)
ax.spines[["top","right"]].set_visible(False)
ax.grid(False)
ax.set_ylabel("Stars (k)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
